    "skillPoints": 8,
    "startingGold": "5d4 x 10 gp",
    "alignment": "Any; scouts in military service are usually lawful",
    "abilitiesNote": "Dexterity helps scouts become stealthy and offsets their light armor. Wisdom supports key perception and wilderness skills such as Spot, Listen, and Survival.",
    "description": "A scout gathers information for any force on the move. In dungeons and wilderness alike, scouts move quickly through difficult terrain, detect enemies before being detected, and give their allies time to prepare for danger.",
    "adventures": "Scouts adventure as military outriders, border foresters, wilderness guides, or independent explorers drawn to the challenge and variety of adventuring life.",
    "characteristics": "A scout combines stealth, observation, mobility, and a skirmishing combat style. She is strongest before battle starts, when she can locate enemies, read terrain, and report what lies ahead, but she can also support a fight with mobile melee or ranged attacks.",
    "religion": "Scouts follow many faiths. Some honor nature deities, but unlike rangers they do not normally draw power from nature itself; they treat terrain as the ground on which they do their work.",
    "background": "Many scouts learn their trade in military service, while others grow up in rural or wild regions and develop their skills through exploration, hunting, guiding, or service to local lords.",
    "races": "Humans, elves, and halflings make especially capable scouts. Dwarves and gnomes can become strong underground scouts, with scout speed helping offset their slower movement.",
    "otherClasses": "Scouts work well with almost any party. They complement louder or slower groups by ranging ahead or guarding the rear, and they also fit naturally into stealth-heavy parties with rogues, rangers, ninjas, and other scouts.",
    "role": "A scout detects threats, searches dangerous areas, handles traps, supports combat as a mobile striker or ranged combatant, and helps prevent the party from being surprised.",
